T1  - Choosing the method of sale: A clinical study of Conrail
AU  - Baldwin, Carliss Y.
AU  - Bhattacharyya, Sugato
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 30
IS  - 1
SP  - 69
EP  - 98
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/11/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-405X(91)90038-L
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304405X9190038L
AB  - This paper analyzes the sale of Conrail (Consolidated Rail Corporation) and finds three problems: first, a contingent claim gave the seller (the U.S. Government) conflicting objectives; second, bidders in the auction valued Conrail differently and thus did not compete effectively; and third, Conrail's management had an information advantage over the seller and outside bidders. These three factors can be present in any corporate divestiture and will tend to decrease the seller's revenue. We discuss how different methods of sale (e.g., two-stage auctions and parallel secret negotiations) will counteract these problems to varying degrees, although we find no single ‘best’ method.
